    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3402612600" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3402612600" />
    <a title="Peter Beck" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/93075324-peter-beck"><img alt="Peter Beck" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564058746p2/93075324.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3402612600?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter Beck" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter Beck" href="/user/show/93075324-peter-beck">Peter Beck</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/93075324-peter-beck?shelf=presidents">presidents</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3402612600" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9921996393042607702">Ms. Millard? More Please! Kudos to Candice for writing a vibrant and moving account of the assassination of James Garfield, America’s 20th president. This is the first time I have read a book that I wish had been twice as long. <br/><br/>Garfield once asked a close friend, “Do you think my name will have a place in human history?” (p. 228). Millard has done more than anyone else to make that happen. For starters, her biography is 20 times more popular than “Dark Horse,” the next most popular biography of </span>
  <span id="freeText9921996393042607702" style="display:none">Ms. Millard? More Please! Kudos to Candice for writing a vibrant and moving account of the assassination of James Garfield, America’s 20th president. This is the first time I have read a book that I wish had been twice as long. <br /><br />Garfield once asked a close friend, “Do you think my name will have a place in human history?” (p. 228). Millard has done more than anyone else to make that happen. For starters, her biography is 20 times more popular than “Dark Horse,” the next most popular biography of Garfield. I had planned to skip all of the presidents between Grant and Teddy, but I wanted to give one of America’s most popular presidential biographers a try.<br /><br />Millard wisely chose a little known but compelling president. Garfield was born into crushing poverty, but became a university president by the age of 26 and a Civil War hero soon after that. His path to the presidency is even more amazing--he had no thought of being president when he went to the 1880 Republican National Convention. He didn’t receive more than one vote until after 30+ rounds of voting. Yet he ultimately defeated Grant and walked away with the nomination in a unanimous vote. Did I mention Garfield also had a wife and five young children that he absolutely adored?<br /><br />Millard also delves into the lives of the key people around Garfield, particularly the three people who would determine his fate--his assassin, deranged job seeker Charles Guiteau, his lead doctor Dr. Bliss (-fully ignorant of germ theory), and the famous inventor who tried to save him, Alexander Graham Bell. Garfield is one of those rare leaders who knew his assassin. Sadly, Garfield’s bullet wound would not have been life threatening had he been in better medical hands. The months of unnecessary pain he endured with grace is heart-breaking. <br /><br />Millard is a masterful scene setter. Like Edmund Morris, she tells you which flowers the president was smelling when a scene unfolds. She also finds wonderful quotes from Garfield and his wife Lucretia (“Crete”). Millard even raises the kind of moral issue I cannot recall encountering in a presidential biography. Charles Guiteau was widely seen as mentally ill, yet his insanity defense failed. Millard simply notes that his execution “accomplished nothing,” (p. 247), other than satisfying the public’s blood lust and a vague sense of retribution. Given the horrors unfolding daily, you will be excused if you missed the announcement last week that the Trump Administration intends to resume federal executions this summer. They would be the first since I changed my own view almost 20 years ago. Oklahoma City Bomber Timothy McVeigh was just as unrepentant as Guiteau. Aside from state-sanctioned murder, what did we accomplish? Fortunately, public opinion has shifted since then. <br /><br />My only disappointment with “Destiny” is that Millard doesn’t give us the full picture of Garfield’s life. Like Steve Inskeep’s “Imperfect Union,” she covers too much ground in too little space (260 pages). At first I thought this was a short book for a short presidency, but I came to see it more as history for impatient, time-starved readers. We get far too few details about Garfield’s life prior to being nominated for president. Unlike Inskeep, Millard had plenty to work with. Like the Adams family, the Garfields kept journals and wrote regularly to one another. <br /><br />Millard does begin each of her 23 chapters with quotes from Garfield. He was clearly a thoughtful and articulate person. I wish I had learned more about him, his family and closest friends. Millard did reconfirm my decision to skip Rutherford and Chester. We will never know if Garfield would have been more successful than they were. I don’t think it is fair to include him in presidential rankings unless they include his posthumous accomplishments--bringing the country (North and South) together and civil service reform.<br /><br />I see that several of my GoodReads friends enjoyed “Dark Horse.” How would you compare it with “Destiny”? I plan to read Millard’s “River of Doubt,” but first I have to finish the Morris TR trilogy. Before that, I may need some founding father and Lincoln wisdom to help me get through the next 134 days (election day). The destiny of our republic is at stake. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9921996393042607702" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


