    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_797121004" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/797121004" />
    <a title="Max" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8079403-max"><img alt="Max" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625519120p2/8079403.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/797121004?book_show_action=true">Dec 22, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Max" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Max" href="/user/show/8079403-max">Max</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8079403-max?shelf=american-history">american-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer797121004" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2164918737947854516">Candice Millard’s biography of James Garfield explores a less well known but meaningful episode in U. S. history. We’ll never know if Garfield would have made the great president everyone felt he would be. But his assassination did have significant impact.<br/><br/>Perhaps the most important was the shared emotion that gave the entire nation, South and North, something to come together over for the first time since the war. Another was abandonment of the spoils system and the implementation of the civil s</span>
  <span id="freeText2164918737947854516" style="display:none">Candice Millard’s biography of James Garfield explores a less well known but meaningful episode in U. S. history. We’ll never know if Garfield would have made the great president everyone felt he would be. But his assassination did have significant impact.<br /><br />Perhaps the most important was the shared emotion that gave the entire nation, South and North, something to come together over for the first time since the war. Another was abandonment of the spoils system and the implementation of the civil service system. Because Garfield’s killer, Charles Guiteau, was a disgruntled seeker of a presidential appointment, many saw this as the prime reason for the killing and thus elimination of patronage as the appropriate remedy. But even after this second presidential assassination in less than twenty years, no protection was provided for the president. That had to wait until the next assassination. Incredible! The more fundamental reason for the killing was simply Guiteau’s insanity and resulting delusions of grandeur. Garfield’s death also profoundly impacted the new president, Chester Arthur, the unlikeliest of presidents. He was chosen to balance the ticket as was Andrew Johnson before him, both with no expectation that they would ever be president. Arthur had been a stooge of the powerful Senator Conkling, a Garfield enemy. Deeply affected by the assassination Arthur did a complete about face, rejected Conkling and adopted Garfield’s policies.<br /><br />The other thought-provoking aspect of Millard’s story is her depiction of the times. It is startling to realize how unsophisticated the institution of the presidency was in 1881. The president had no security assigned to him, people could enter the White House at will, he had one secretary to handle his affairs, he traveled on common carriers like any other citizen, and he lived in a run down, dilapidated White House. The U. S. was a substantial country by 1881 and to think its chief executive lived and worked like this is mindboggling. Similarly, the abysmal state of medical care and arrogance of American doctors is given much attention by Millard. By and large the American medical establishment rejected the use of antiseptic medicine though well established in Europe and practiced by Joseph Lister for 15 years with excellent results. On top of this doctors engaged in turf battles at the expense of their patients and most notably Garfield. More than the shooter, the doctors killed Garfield with their unsanitary practices and egotism.<br /><br />Destiny of the Republic is a good book showing how backward America was at a time of great discoveries and advances. As usual the times were way ahead of people’s ability to deal with the changed world they lived in. Recommended for those who want to find out just how far we have come. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2164918737947854516" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

